      "text": "The classic template for a pattern description, in Alexander's *Pattern language*,  has these elements:\n- Distinctive, evocative name\n- Evocative image\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "a934fe5a2885db6e",
      "text": "- Context - the patterns that this pattern helps to complete; the elements of the situation in which the pattern becomes needed\n- Keynote - A summary paragraph, equivalent to the 'reference' of a wiki page. This outlines the challenge, tension or contradiction that the pattern is a practical response to\n- Siblings - Actually, not in Alexander. These are patterns that resonate with or affiliate with the present pattern, without being (hierarchical) context. Peers, not details, not parents\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "c158f60bf34248df",
      "text": "- Back story - The research, the narratives, the history, the evidence, the precedents, the journalism, the mythology, the disputes.\n> This can be very substantial - effectively a sub-family of notes, a notebook-within-a-notebook. Organised under a number of categories to constitute a (searchanble) library. Shown on this page, categories of back-story are: concepts, stories, skills, genres (adopted from Cook & Brown's 'generative [[Dance of knowing]]')\n\n"
    },
